body.plain: their love is conditional, but isn’t yours too?

annotations:
So I’ll have to let him go
 We sometimes fit, but we always lie
 And he thinks we could make it work
 But only when he’s drunk
This person will not work for her like, perhaps, this friend will. The relationship is far more toxic.
I wish that I was going to sleep

The narrator later references how perhaps the friend  could “make [her] fall asleep when [they’re] holding her” however at this point, she wants to sleep alone and is not interested in this romantic moment.
Friend, old friend,

This is a person the narrator has known all her life, or at least for a good majority of it.

Since the rest of the verse suggests this friend likes her romantically, the double-insistence here that he is just a “friend” suggests friendzoning.

What’s the hurry? We’re not ready
 We’ve got plenty of time
Later referenced in the bridge, the narrator is a “slow mover” hence not wanting to hurry.

And maybe one day we’ll get married
 Maybe fall in love
The narrator, after acknowledging in the bridge that she is a slow mover, has decided that maybe she will one day love the friend who loves her already. However, as a slow mover, this will take time.

Friend, I am a slow, slow mover
 Friend, I am a slow, slow girl

The narrator is suggesting that things take more time for her.

To reference the fire motif a bit more, a “slow burn” is a technique typically used in film and television, wherein two characters take a long time––the course of a few season or the whole movie, typically––to finally get together.
Go get set on fire

The second iteration of the fire motif.

She is encouraging the friend to “go get set on fire” i.e. to go fall in love with someone else.

You think you could help me swim
 But I’ve already sunk
The friend from verse 1 wants to help the narrator get over this other boy, but the narrator believes she is beyond fixing.

There’s someone else but I twist all of
 His words and he twists mine
The narrator has a separate interest outside this friend who likes her. The relationship appears to be more toxic.
Try set me on fire

The first of the “fire” motif in this song, she is challenging the friend to try to “set her on fire.”

Fire is commonly used as a symbol of passion, love, etc. The narrator wants to feel something and wants this friend to try.

description.plain:
On “Missing Me,” Angie expresses the intense emotion of telling someone that you love that they are doing you wrong. Even if she is considering leaving – she hasn’t made up her mind. She told Richard Kingsmill on triple j:

It definitely is quite an open and honest song… It felt like a lot of things, it’s sad but it also makes me feel powerful when I sing it.

description.plain:
Angie’s Instagram bio reads: “90% spaghetti bolognese”. Pasta is an ode to lethargy. It’s a dryly funny tribute to procrastination and mid-twenties malaise. She gives a voice to people who are in flux, wrapped up in their mundane daily lives. At the same this song is also about being scared and excited about what the future holds.
